<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-728-671  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 728 671.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Weekly  Dec 13 1990 n1243 p12(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>A question of morals and US role-playing games. (The US SecretService's raid on Steve Jackson Games Inc.) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Masters, Phil.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>In 1990 the US Secret Service made a ballyhooed raid on SteveJackson Games Inc of Austin, TX, seizing equipment and printouts.andO;The Secret Service apparently believes that a book the firm wasset to publish, 'Cyberpunk' by Loyd Blankenship, containedinformation on how to commit computer crime.andP;  A reading of thetext reveals that is hardly the case.andP;  Well-written but scarcelyoriginal, 'Cyberpunk' concentrates on a type of role-playingcomputer game in which characters are ruthless and often amoral.andO;Perhaps that is what the government's men were worried about.andP;  Thebook contains only a little technical information that could beeven marginally useful to a budding hacker.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Steve Jackson Games Inc. (Investigations).andO;Topic:     Computer HackersComputer GamesLegal IssuesInvestigationsUnited States. Secret Service.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>